re, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Pearce Hall, Yorkshire, , England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Freston, Suffolk, England":"Freston, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1540–2 September 1600":"about 1540–2 September 1600","1540–1600":"1540–1600","1555–1605":"1555–1605","1544–Female":"1544–Deceased","1564–Female":"1564–Deceased","1500–1553":"1500–1553","1504–Female":"1504–Deceased","2 September 1600":"2 September 1600","1571":"1571","18 June 1564":"18 June 1564","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1500":"1500","1544":"1544","1555":"1555","1587":"1587","1553":"1553","Abt 1563":"about 1563","1531":"1531","1564":"1564","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","about 1540":"about 1540","1605":"1605","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","Of, Freston, Suffolk, England":"Freston, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Pearce Hall, Yorkshire, , England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Freston, Suffolk, England":"Freston, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pearse","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Pierce  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pierce","meanings":["English, Welsh, and Irish: from the Anglo-Norman French and Middle English personal name <i>Piers</i>, <i>Peres</i>, <i>Peris</i>, an Old French nominative of <i>Pierre</i> or <i>Per</i>, the French form of   Peter  . <i>Pierce</i> is especially frequent in northwestern Wales and Lancashire, while <i>Pearce</i> is the more common spelling in the rest of England. In Ireland <i>Pierce</i> and <i>Pearse</i> represent a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Piarais</b> ‘son of <i>Piaras</i>’, a Gaelicized form of <i>Piers</i>.","Americanized form of some similar-sounding Jewish surname.","History: Franklin Pierce (1804–69), 14th president of the US, was born in Hillsborough, NH, on the New England frontier. His English ancestor Thomas Pierce emigrated to Charlestown, MA, in 1633/34."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":9,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":18,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":29,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":31,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":45,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":47,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":60,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Rob